The tool had a public release in March 2014 to a general audience, but the impacts during its development (before and during the award) have been far reaching. 
1. Two other data sources have been added and the number of users has been greatly increasing which has added value to natural history collections by increasing their effectiveness, access and usefulness.
2. Increasing the impact and usefulness of citizen science collection, through the addition of data sources from INaturalist and Picasa (Google images), as well as the existing services from Flickr.
3. Increasing the effectiveness, access and usefulness of social media for conservation and species observations, by using iNaturalist, Picasa and Flickr for species observations
4. Our web analytics show the Number of unique users is over 8,300 since 1st April 2014, which has shown a 60% increase in the last 10 months. Each user spending on average 4 minutes with the tool.
5. Our web analytics suggests we regularly have 100's of users with over 60 thousand page views and most are returning visitors. The majority of users are from Brisbane, Panama, Brno, Edinburgh and London.
6. GeoCAT has now been cited 155 times in the scientific literature (over 100 time since the NERC sponsored release one year and two months ago) and assuming two to ten assessments, is carried per publication indicates well over 312 - 1500 assessments using GeoCAT to calculate range based metrics for Red Listing. Furthermore, 209 assessments have referenced use of GeoCAT on the IUCN Red List.
7. Assessment have ranged well beyond plants to other groups in the terrestrial and marine environments
8. GeoCAT is being used by IUCN Red List Unit staff during training sessions and it is recognised as one of a suite of mapping tools used for Red Listing. 
We will continue to develop the training material including screencasts to promote the use of this tool which will increase its reach and impact for scientists, conservationists, educators and the general public in the future. Also we envisage that the open source tool and algorithms will allow the research to be taken further by others as well as this research group (as the EUBON funding shows).</gtr:description><gtr:firstYearOfImpact>2014</gtr:firstYearOfImpact><gtr:id>E62A233A-EE5E-4A0D-A88E-6C42EB5ABF1D</gtr:id><gtr:impactTypes><gtr:impactType>Societal</gtr:impactType></gtr:impactTypes><gtr:outcomeId>545cd9ccb80e72.07744512</gtr:outcomeId><gtr:sector>Education,Environment,Culture, Heritage, Museums and Collections,Other</gtr:sector></gtr:impactSummaryOutput></gtr:impactSummaryOutputs><gtr:intellectualPropertyOutputs/><gtr:keyFindingsOutput><gtr:description>The research grant was for the development and public release of GeoCAT (Geospatial Conservation Assessment Tool). GeoCAT is an open source, browser based tool that performs real time geospatial analysis to ease the process of conducting species conservation assessments (see geocat.kew.org).
Major achievement to date (February 2016) are:
1) Several public releases of tool from beta to a stable version in March 2014, with many bugs fixed
2) The tool has been coded and enhanced allowing improved research methods and usability. The following features have been implemented within this period of development:
o Methodology and interface developed to handle multiple species - a highly requested feature from users.
o Other occurrence data sources have be added including the citizen Science project iNaturalist and Picasa images
o The ability to record temporal decline of distributions for example based on deforestation
o Options to display environmental data from other mapping sources have been added e.g. web mapping server, CartoDB, Google Fusion Tables and KML, which can be easily displayed in the map interface. Also addition of deforestation layer is available
o Behind the scenes improvement for speed, data integration and standardisation
3) Increased research capacity generated from training for specialists. GeoCAT has been demonstrated at many times (at least 50 times since March 2014) at IUCN training courses as well as at Kew Gardens.</gtr:description><gtr:exploitationPathways>The initial tool (Version 1) has was developed and released in March 2014, we have been working on and with continue to improve training, online help and snagging. 
Beyond the end of the funding this tool has continued to evolve and as it is open source the code and algorithms can be used by other groups, the GitHub repository has already been branched nine times (N.B. GitHub is an online repository distribution network of code, which others can freely download or fork and therefore develop themselves and resubmit). Building on the success of the NERC release further funding for the tool has been granted to IUCN/WCMC under the EU BON funding umbrella to develop the tool further. We are in talks with IUCN/WCMC on this development but we would envision that the GeoCAT will have the potential to develop in the following areas:
? Further Integration with other systems i.e. providing an occurrence output file compatible with IUCN's Species Information Service
? Addition of new algorithms i.e. minimum area of occupancy, fragmentation index, vegetation change, population change trends, Species distribution modelling coupled with climate change modelling
