Major achievement to date (March 2017) are:
1) Several public releases of tool from beta to a stable version in March 2014, with many bugs fixed
2) The tool has been coded and enhanced allowing improved research methods and usability. The following features have been implemented within this period of development:
o Methodology and interface developed to handle multiple species - a highly requested feature from users.
o Other occurrence data sources have been added including the citizen Science project iNaturalist and Picasa images
o The ability to record temporal decline of distributions for example based on deforestation
o Options to display environmental data from other mapping sources have been added e.g. web mapping server, CartoDB, Google Fusion Tables and KML, which can be easily displayed in the map interface. Also, addition of deforestation layer is available
o Behind the scenes improvement for speed, data integration and standardisation

